n policy behavior. She examines self-monitoring among national leaders and advisers and shows that while high self-monitors modify their behavior strategically to cultivate image-enhancing status, low self-monitors are less likely to change their behavior in response to reputation concerns.Exploring self-monitoring through case studies of foreign policy crises during the terms of U.S. presidents Carter, Reagan, and Clinton, Yarhi-Milo disproves the notion that hawks are always more likely than doves to fight for reputation. Instead, Yarhi-Milo demonstrates that a decision maker's propensity for impression management is directly associated with the use of force to restore a reputation for resolve on the international stage.Who Fights for Reputation offers a brand-new understanding of the pivotal influence that psychological factors have on political leadership, military engagement, and the protection of public prestige.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Sep 2021) 0aHeads of statevCase studies. 0aInternational relationsxDecision makingvCase studies. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Process / General.2bisacsh  aAmazon Mechanical Turk.  aAmerican adults.  aAmerican presidents.  aBill Clinton.  aCyrus Vance.  aIsraeli Jewish adults.  aJimmy Carter.  aRonald Reagan.  aUS presidents.  aUS reputation.  aZbigniew Brzezinski.  acase studies.  acrisis decision making.  adecision making.  adispositional theory.  aforeign policy behavior.  aforeign policy.  ahawkishness.  ahigh self-monitors.  ainternational conflict.  ainternational crises.  ainternational politics.  ainternational relations.  ainternational reputation.  aleaders.  alow self-monitors.  amilitarized interstate disputes.  amilitary action.  amilitary assertiveness.  amilitary engagement.  amilitary force.  amil